It’s the last day of my life. The doctors have done everything they could, but the cancer has spread too quickly. They have told me that there is no hope. My family and friends surround my bed, crying. I am only sixteen, and this is supposed to be the happiest time of my life. I should be planning for my senior prom, the rest of my high school career, college, and the rest of my life. I should be planning my future with my friends, the love of my life, and my family. I should be thinking about what I want to do when I grow up. I should be worrying about the little things, like my next test grade, and the bigger things, like the new car I’m going to buy. I should be thinking about how I am going to spend my summer vacation. But I can’t. All I can think about is how my family is going to get through this without me. I’m not going to be able to help my mom and dad anymore. I’m not going to be able to watch my little brother grow up. I’m not going to be able to graduate from high school. I’m not going to be able to take care of my grandparents when they get old. I’m not going to be able to get married and have children. I’m not going to be able to live the rest of my life. I’m going to die today. I have no regrets. I have lived a good life. I’ve made my family and friends happy. I have been a good daughter, sister, granddaughter, niece, cousin, and friend. I’ve lived my life to the fullest, and I’ve done everything I wanted to do. I’ve experienced everything I wanted to experience. I’ve seen the world. I’ve climbed the
